{
  "local_port": 43926,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "My laptop is showing limited connectivity to WiFi while other on other laptop working properly?",
  "response": "If your laptop is showing \"Limited Connectivity\" to WiFi while other devices are working fine, it could be due to several reasons. Here are some troubleshooting steps to help resolve the issue:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Restart Your Laptop and Router**\n   - Turn off your laptop and restart it.\n   - Also, restart your WiFi router by unplugging it for 30 seconds and plugging it back in.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Forget and Reconnect to the WiFi Network**\n   - Go to your WiFi settings, select the network, and choose \"Forget.\"\n   - Reconnect by entering the password again.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Check IP Address Settings**\n   - Open **Command Prompt** (Windows) and type `ipconfig`.\n   - Look for the \"Default Gateway\" and \"IPv4 Address\" under your WiFi adapter.\n   - If the IP address starts with `169.254.x.x`, it means your laptop is not getting a proper IP address from the router.\n     - Solution: Set your IP address to obtain automatically:\n       1. Go to **Network and Sharing Center** > **Change adapter settings**.\n       2. Right-click your WiFi adapter > **Properties**.\n       3. Select **Internet Protocol Version 4 (TCP/IPv4)** > **Properties**.\n       4. Ensure both options are set to \"Obtain an IP address automatically\" and \"Obtain DNS server address automatically.\"\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Update WiFi Drivers**\n   - Outdated or corrupt WiFi drivers can cause connectivity issues.\n   - Go to your laptop manufacturer\u2019s website or the WiFi adapter manufacturer\u2019s website and download the latest drivers.\n   - Alternatively, use Device Manager:\n     1. Press `Win + X` > **Device Manager**.\n     2. Expand **Network adapters**.\n     3. Right-click your WiFi adapter > **Update driver**.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Reset Network Settings**\n   - Open **Command Prompt** as Administrator and run the following commands:\n     - `netsh winsock reset`\n     - `netsh int ip reset`\n     - `ipconfig /release`\n     - `ipconfig /renew`\n   - Restart your laptop after running these commands.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Disable IPv6**\n   - Sometimes, disabling IPv6 can resolve connectivity issues:\n     1. Go to **Network and Sharing Center** > **Change adapter settings**.\n     2. Right-click your WiFi adapter > **Properties**.\n     3. Uncheck **Internet Protocol Version 6 (TCP/IPv6)**.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Check for Interference**\n   - Ensure there are no physical obstructions or devices (like microwaves or cordless phones) causing interference with your WiFi signal.\n   - Try moving closer to the router.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Check for Software Conflicts**\n   - Temporarily disable any antivirus or firewall software to see if it\u2019s blocking the connection.\n   - Also, check if any VPN software is causing the issue.\n\n---\n\n### 9. **Flush DNS Cache**\n   - Open **Command Prompt** and type:\n     - `ipconfig /flushdns`\n   - Restart your laptop.\n\n---\n\n### 10. **Factory Reset Network Settings (Windows 10/11)**\n   - Go to **Settings** > **Network & Internet** > **Status** > **Network reset**.\n   - This will reset all network adapters and settings to default.\n\n---\n\n### 11. **Test with a Different Network**\n   - Connect your laptop to a different WiFi network (e.g., a mobile hotspot) to see if the issue is specific to your router.\n\n---\n\n### 12. **Check Router Settings**\n   - Log in to your router\u2019s admin panel (usually accessible via `192.168.1.1` or `192.168.0.1`).\n   - Ensure that the router is not blocking your laptop\u2019s MAC address or IP address.\n\n---\n\n### 13. **Reset WiFi Adapter**\n   - Go to **Device Manager** > **Network adapters**.\n   - Right-click your WiFi adapter > **Disable device**, then right-click again and select **Enable device**.\n\n---\n\nIf none of these steps resolve the issue, there could be a hardware problem with your laptop\u2019s WiFi adapter. In that case, consider contacting a technician or using an external USB WiFi adapter.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
